1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:10,550 --> 00:00:11,950
You're not going to the Badger?

3
00:00:12,020 --> 00:00:12,620
I am.

4
00:00:13,150 --> 00:00:14,760
So why are you having bottled ones?

5
00:00:14,760 --> 00:00:15,440
Appetizer.

6
00:00:17,650 --> 00:00:20,420
Wait, I thought you wanted to enjoy draft beer today.

7
00:00:20,750 --> 00:00:21,850
Enjoy draft?

8
00:00:22,080 --> 00:00:22,540
Yeah.

9
00:00:23,550 --> 00:00:24,850
Today more than usual?

10
00:00:25,350 --> 00:00:26,150
Oh yeah.

11
00:00:26,210 --> 00:00:26,790
Why?

12
00:00:26,790 --> 00:00:28,370
The big bash isn't till tomorrow.

13
00:00:28,550 --> 00:00:29,950
What do you mean tomorrow?

14
00:00:30,350 --> 00:00:31,810
Tomorrow there won't be anything left?

15
00:00:31,950 --> 00:00:34,850
Wait, Simona clearly said we'd get smashed there tomorrow.

16
00:00:35,550 --> 00:00:38,850
She said the Badger would get demolished.

17
00:00:41,380 --> 00:00:41,980
What?

18
00:02:10,450 --> 00:02:11,530
Last beer.

19
00:02:14,550 --> 00:02:16,350
No griping, the Badger is done.

20
00:02:16,850 --> 00:02:17,950
Send it around.

21
00:02:18,550 --> 00:02:21,950
The last beer from the Badger belongs to the most loyal regular.

22
00:02:42,950 --> 00:02:46,950
Then the last beer arrives and none of us knows about it.

23
00:02:54,150 --> 00:02:55,250
You talking to us again?

24
00:02:55,670 --> 00:02:56,190
No.

25
00:02:58,850 --> 00:03:00,810
Come on, don't be silly, bro, it's not our fault.

26
00:03:00,810 --> 00:03:02,130
It is, because you don't care.

27
00:03:02,450 --> 00:03:03,710
I happen to care.

28
00:03:03,710 --> 00:03:04,170
Yeah.

29
00:03:05,050 --> 00:03:07,550
So the Badger means nothing to you.

30
00:03:07,750 --> 00:03:12,910
Six times a week pints, my puked-up toilets, and smoke bombs at every football match so the guys felt like they were in the cauldron.

31
00:03:12,910 --> 00:03:13,690
And what about me?

32
00:03:14,750 --> 00:03:16,250
You didn't bother me that much.

33
00:03:16,250 --> 00:03:21,120
Bro, I'm not happy about them selling burgers here either, but I just can't do anything about it.

34
00:03:21,120 --> 00:03:22,080
Because you're a coward.

35
00:03:22,650 --> 00:03:26,600
So I'm supposed to chain myself to the fridge and swallow the key?

36
00:03:26,600 --> 00:03:28,140
Like you in '75?

37
00:03:28,240 --> 00:03:28,900
And why not?

38
00:03:29,850 --> 00:03:31,540
Because I'm not crazy.

39
00:03:31,540 --> 00:03:33,140
What happened in '75?

40
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:37,040
We were moving to Karlin and someone snitched on Ozzak that they don't serve minors there.

41
00:03:37,220 --> 00:03:38,300
That's nonsense.

42
00:03:38,440 --> 00:03:40,040
In Karlin they always served anyone.

43
00:03:40,480 --> 00:03:42,680
And we found that out too, eventually we got there.

44
00:03:43,150 --> 00:03:46,420
But before Dad dragged him out of the pub, he drank away the fridge with the chain.

45
00:03:46,420 --> 00:03:47,540
Well, that's his protests for you.

46
00:03:47,780 --> 00:03:48,600
At least I'm not a coward.

47
00:03:49,750 --> 00:03:52,840
And what are you doing now to keep your favorite pub from closing, huh?

48
00:03:53,150 --> 00:03:53,950
I need to chain myself up.

49
00:04:01,150 --> 00:04:05,250
I'm telling you for the tenth and last time, unlock yourself right now and go home.

50
00:04:05,300 --> 00:04:05,740
Never.

51
00:04:05,740 --> 00:04:08,450
So that's why he wanted the key from me, that rascal.

52
00:04:11,350 --> 00:04:14,050
God, that's my bicycle chain.

53
00:04:14,350 --> 00:04:15,830
Why did you give him the key?

54
00:04:15,950 --> 00:04:17,050
He said he wanted to go for a ride.

55
00:04:17,450 --> 00:04:18,930
And that didn't seem weird to you?

56
00:04:18,950 --> 00:04:19,750
It did.

57
00:04:19,850 --> 00:04:21,540
He can't even ride that bike.

58
00:04:21,540 --> 00:04:22,440
What do you mean he can't?

59
00:04:22,440 --> 00:04:23,650
I ride it.

60
00:04:23,950 --> 00:04:25,750
Is that the bike you walk to the post office with?

61
00:04:25,850 --> 00:04:29,150
Look, Simona, it doesn't seem far on foot, but it's actually quite a hike.

62
00:04:30,150 --> 00:04:31,410
Give me that key right now.

63
00:04:31,410 --> 00:04:31,810
I can't.

64
00:04:32,450 --> 00:04:34,450
I'd say the key will turn up at the earliest...

65
00:04:35,050 --> 00:04:36,050
Tomorrow after lunch.

66
00:04:37,550 --> 00:04:38,950
Dude, he swallowed it again?

67
00:04:39,250 --> 00:04:42,050
The Smurf didn't really want to, but I helped him with a chaser.

68
00:04:42,260 --> 00:04:42,660
You...

69
00:04:43,480 --> 00:04:44,580
That's manly.

70
00:04:45,100 --> 00:04:46,260
No, young man!

71
00:04:46,380 --> 00:04:47,640
That's irresponsible!

72
00:04:47,800 --> 00:04:49,840
I'm going to have an unlocked bike all night!

73
00:04:49,940 --> 00:04:51,140
And do you know how they steal around here?

74
00:04:51,260 --> 00:04:52,720
Yeah, they stole my pub!

75
00:04:52,940 --> 00:04:54,260
Nobody would steal that bike.

76
00:04:54,550 --> 00:04:55,650
At most for scrap.

77
00:04:56,550 --> 00:04:57,850
It's got brass, different handlebars.

78
00:04:58,150 --> 00:05:00,150
Horvat said brass prices went up.

79
00:05:01,310 --> 00:05:01,790
Jesus!

80
00:05:09,450 --> 00:05:12,050
So, who's in favor of all of us chaining ourselves here?

81
00:05:13,280 --> 00:05:13,960
So that's two.

82
00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:14,980
That's a clear win.

83
00:05:16,850 --> 00:05:17,250
No, damn.

84
00:05:18,100 --> 00:05:19,040
It's a tie.

85
00:05:19,600 --> 00:05:20,120
Damn!

86
00:05:20,500 --> 00:05:21,560
I don't want to.

87
00:05:21,560 --> 00:05:24,850
We'll be heroes and I'll tell you where I hid the knitting needles.

88
00:05:28,150 --> 00:05:30,170
Jesus, Sasha, cut this nonsense.

89
00:05:30,450 --> 00:05:33,750
In the morning they'll cut Ozzak loose anyway and the pub gets demolished.

90
00:05:34,350 --> 00:05:38,350
And we'll see what a hero you are when you explain to Kobra why you missed the test.

91
00:05:39,050 --> 00:05:40,550
Mr. Ozzak will write us excuse notes.

92
00:05:41,750 --> 00:05:42,950
Kobra is still there?

93
00:05:43,550 --> 00:05:44,450
She taught you too?

94
00:05:45,750 --> 00:05:47,150
Excuse notes don't work on her.

95
00:05:47,850 --> 00:05:51,150
Once we had to rehearse with the band to open for the executioners and we had to practice.

96
00:05:51,550 --> 00:05:53,150
I wrote that my brother and I had lice.

97
00:05:53,650 --> 00:05:57,750
Kobra sniffed out where we were rehearsing and came to inspect our heads.

98
00:05:58,750 --> 00:06:00,550
My brother got in big trouble for it.

99
00:06:01,350 --> 00:06:02,220
Just Dad?

100
00:06:02,550 --> 00:06:03,850
Luckily, I actually had them.

101
00:06:05,050 --> 00:06:06,790
Wow, you really showed her.

102
00:06:07,150 --> 00:06:08,650
Even Voracek couldn't do that to her.

103
00:06:08,650 --> 00:06:09,730
He's a moron.

104
00:06:09,730 --> 00:06:11,750
Actually, he had it all planned out.

105
00:06:12,150 --> 00:06:13,050
Planned out?

106
00:06:13,350 --> 00:06:17,550
Telling Kobra that three unknown men attacked him in the park and tied him to a tree with a belt?

107
00:06:18,190 --> 00:06:20,670
If that belt hadn't been traced back to Sandy, it would've worked perfectly.

108
00:06:20,670 --> 00:06:25,150
It wouldn't have, there'd have been a reconstruction, like when Krupackova claimed she was assaulted.

109
00:06:25,250 --> 00:06:28,750
And Kobra proved that such a position doesn't even exist.

110
00:06:29,150 --> 00:06:31,950
She moved up to an honorary third place on the Dutohlav ranking.

111
00:06:31,950 --> 00:06:32,810
Right behind Lexa.

112
00:06:33,570 --> 00:06:34,790
Voracek and I are tied.

113
00:06:35,950 --> 00:06:40,250
Hey, Mr. Pacovsky, did you know the Mr. Dutohlav the ranking is named after?

114
00:06:40,380 --> 00:06:43,480
He was the only student of hers dumber than Lexa and Voracek.

115
00:06:43,480 --> 00:06:49,650
I swore I'd never work as a waitress again, but I'm not leaving my dishes behind.

116
00:06:51,350 --> 00:06:52,350
Goodbye, Badger.

117
00:06:53,150 --> 00:06:55,550
We spent the best years of my life together.

118
00:06:56,150 --> 00:07:00,450
If you were a person, I'd spit in your face, you disgusting dive.

119
00:07:01,220 --> 00:07:01,940
Let's go.

120
00:07:04,450 --> 00:07:05,850
Hold on to this, uncle.

121
00:07:06,550 --> 00:07:07,950
You won't need it on the toilet.

122
00:07:08,050 --> 00:07:10,990
Mom, Mr. Ozzak isn't some amateur.

123
00:07:10,990 --> 00:07:12,410
He's got this all figured out, right?

124
00:07:13,150 --> 00:07:14,150
For sure.

125
00:07:14,450 --> 00:07:16,850
Maybe one day I'll start missing all this.

126
00:07:17,450 --> 00:07:18,850
You'll slap me a few times, right?

127
00:07:21,750 --> 00:07:26,750
Lexa, come by in the morning and bring me a bottle.

128
00:07:26,750 --> 00:07:27,450
Of what?

129
00:07:27,950 --> 00:07:29,850
Doesn't matter, just make sure it's really big.

130
00:07:46,150 --> 00:07:46,910
What's going on?

131
00:07:46,910 --> 00:07:49,000
Thieving bastards.

132
00:07:51,950 --> 00:07:53,050
Only this was left.

133
00:07:53,250 --> 00:07:54,650
They actually stole the bike?

134
00:07:54,850 --> 00:07:56,350
We're a nation of thieves.

135
00:07:57,550 --> 00:08:00,350
At least tourists will stop photographing you on the way to the post office.

136
00:08:00,550 --> 00:08:02,750
How can you make light of this?

137
00:08:03,050 --> 00:08:04,530
It was an old wreck.

138
00:08:04,530 --> 00:08:04,970
But mine!

139
00:08:05,450 --> 00:08:06,950
It had collector's value.

140
00:08:07,150 --> 00:08:08,790
You know Alla Pugacheva gave it to me?

141
00:08:08,790 --> 00:08:09,090
I know.

142
00:08:10,450 --> 00:08:12,450
But I don't know who Alla Pugacheva is.

143
00:08:14,100 --> 00:08:15,320
I already called the police.

144
00:08:15,500 --> 00:08:16,120
They'll be here right away.

145
00:08:16,550 --> 00:08:17,250
Really?

146
00:08:17,650 --> 00:08:18,700
Over an old Ukrainian bike?

147
00:08:18,700 --> 00:08:19,200
Yeah.

148
00:08:19,850 --> 00:08:22,050
They said they had nothing better to do.

149
00:08:29,050 --> 00:08:31,150
I'm looking for someone in the culture department.

150
00:08:31,850 --> 00:08:33,150
Department of Agriculture.

151
00:08:34,190 --> 00:08:35,850
Oh, you've merged them.

152
00:08:36,150 --> 00:08:37,190
Right, thanks.

153
00:08:38,550 --> 00:08:39,960
Good morning, Divicova.

154
00:08:40,150 --> 00:08:42,050
Lots of sunshine for your dry meadow.

155
00:08:42,950 --> 00:08:45,520
Right, you'd rather need some rain.

156
00:08:45,520 --> 00:08:47,600
Well then, may it rain for you.

157
00:08:49,950 --> 00:08:56,530
No, no, I understand of course, it must be terrible when it hasn't rained for two months.

158
00:08:56,530 --> 00:08:58,290
But why am I calling you?

159
00:08:58,390 --> 00:09:01,810
I'm a music manager and I have an offer for you.

160
00:09:01,810 --> 00:09:06,850
Surely you've heard that the famous singer Tommy Paci is planning a comeback tour.

161
00:09:07,650 --> 00:09:08,850
Tommy Paci?

162
00:09:09,070 --> 00:09:09,750
Yes.

163
00:09:10,090 --> 00:09:10,770
No.

164
00:09:12,250 --> 00:09:15,630
Well, I don't know if he's the one who looks like your agronomist.

165
00:09:16,050 --> 00:09:18,210
Because I don't know what your agronomist looks like.

166
00:09:18,210 --> 00:09:18,970
Does he have a mustache?

167
00:09:19,750 --> 00:09:21,250
Then it's not him.

168
00:09:21,450 --> 00:09:24,950
But maybe you'll remember his famous song.

169
00:09:25,750 --> 00:09:28,450
You'll bite into me like rain.

170
00:09:29,150 --> 00:09:29,650
So, you like it?

171
00:09:30,810 --> 00:09:31,290
Excellent!

172
00:09:33,350 --> 00:09:36,950
Well, I've never had a request for a concert in a field before.

173
00:09:38,050 --> 00:09:39,350
And where will the audience be?

174
00:09:39,550 --> 00:09:40,450
There won't be one.

175
00:09:41,450 --> 00:09:42,850
Singing to the sky?

176
00:09:43,450 --> 00:09:44,850
And how many times in a row?

177
00:09:45,650 --> 00:09:49,410
Well, well, we're open to unconventional concerts.

178
00:09:49,410 --> 00:09:51,610
Of course it depends on your budget.

179
00:09:52,950 --> 00:09:53,650
Right.

180
00:09:54,350 --> 00:09:56,520
No rain for two months, I understand.

181
00:09:56,520 --> 00:09:57,420
Goodbye then.

182
00:09:57,680 --> 00:10:13,980
What kind of an idiot are you, huh?

183
00:10:14,060 --> 00:10:14,880
I don't get it.

184
00:10:14,980 --> 00:10:15,920
I couldn't brake.

185
00:10:16,850 --> 00:10:18,200
Can't brake a bulldozer.

186
00:10:18,200 --> 00:10:18,640
Idiot.

187
00:10:18,640 --> 00:10:20,550
A rabbit jumped out in front of me.

188
00:10:21,150 --> 00:10:22,000
A rabbit, dude.

189
00:10:22,350 --> 00:10:23,150
In the city.

190
00:10:23,240 --> 00:10:23,940
Idiot.

191
00:10:23,940 --> 00:10:26,950
No, it's the kind of transmission.

192
00:10:27,050 --> 00:10:29,050
Slow is turtle and fast is rabbit.

193
00:10:29,610 --> 00:10:30,690
A transmission for idiots.

194
00:10:30,690 --> 00:10:32,450
And you can't even handle that.

195
00:10:33,550 --> 00:10:34,950
And you're the bulldozer for the cleanup.

196
00:10:36,550 --> 00:10:37,450
Start working then.

197
00:10:38,350 --> 00:10:40,650
Boss, he said I shouldn't.

198
00:10:41,600 --> 00:10:42,040
Idiot.

199
00:10:42,040 --> 00:10:45,350
Don't you know that bulldozers shake their heads when they mean yes?

200
00:10:46,750 --> 00:10:48,150
Should we take the second floor too?

201
00:10:49,150 --> 00:10:50,750
No, boss.

202
00:10:52,350 --> 00:10:53,450
Watch out for this.

203
00:10:55,680 --> 00:10:56,500
Hey, Todor!

204
00:10:57,450 --> 00:11:02,850
Grab a shovel and start working, otherwise we'll never demolish this dive.

205
00:11:03,250 --> 00:11:05,720
Hey, he's on a chain.

206
00:11:10,350 --> 00:11:12,850
So much for Bulgarians being unreliable.

207
00:11:13,150 --> 00:11:16,030
Come on, can't we solve this like normal people?

208
00:11:16,550 --> 00:11:17,650
They're people too.

209
00:11:18,850 --> 00:11:21,160
Hey, Todor, don't be afraid of anything.

210
00:11:21,550 --> 00:11:28,280
The big guy's got bolt cutters in the cab, he'll do snip snip and we'll start demolishing.

211
00:11:28,280 --> 00:11:29,140
I'm not going anywhere.

212
00:11:31,450 --> 00:11:32,650
Hey, he speaks Czech.

213
00:11:33,150 --> 00:11:34,950
I can hear that too, idiot.

214
00:11:36,350 --> 00:11:37,050
What do you mean you're not going?

215
00:11:37,370 --> 00:11:37,990
I'm not going.

216
00:11:39,250 --> 00:11:40,150
You're not Bulgarian?

217
00:11:41,750 --> 00:11:42,850
So what are you doing here?

218
00:11:43,450 --> 00:11:44,210
I'm protesting.

219
00:11:44,650 --> 00:11:46,050
Protesting against what?

220
00:11:46,650 --> 00:11:47,950
Against tearing down pubs.

221
00:11:50,150 --> 00:11:52,350
Big guy.

222
00:11:53,050 --> 00:11:55,350
This gentleman is protesting against us.

223
00:11:58,850 --> 00:12:00,150
What do we do with him?

224
00:12:01,150 --> 00:12:02,050
I'll go around him.

225
00:12:04,850 --> 00:12:05,750
For God's sake.

226
00:12:06,250 --> 00:12:07,150
Why me?

227
00:12:08,050 --> 00:12:09,350
Why always me?

228
00:12:10,050 --> 00:12:13,850
Why do I always get stuck with an idiot for a bulldozer operator?

229
00:12:14,150 --> 00:12:17,650
And a job that's been screwed up from the start.

230
00:12:19,050 --> 00:12:24,150
Look, we're going for bolt cutters and in a minute you'll be protesting outside.

231
00:12:25,050 --> 00:12:25,610
Boss?

232
00:12:25,770 --> 00:12:26,170
Yeah?

233
00:12:26,950 --> 00:12:29,150
And how many bulldozer operators have you had?

234
00:12:30,150 --> 00:12:30,950
Just you.

235
00:12:37,550 --> 00:12:38,250
Police!

236
00:12:39,050 --> 00:12:40,350
Coming!

237
00:12:42,150 --> 00:12:45,050
Good morning, Mr. Pacovsky, Iva won't be going to school today, it's already half past seven.

238
00:12:45,610 --> 00:12:46,170
Jesus.

239
00:12:47,750 --> 00:12:50,120
Iva, get up, we overslept!

240
00:12:50,250 --> 00:12:52,750
Iva, hurry up, we only have five...

241
00:12:53,380 --> 00:12:55,220
Someone was supposed to have the alarm clock and phone here.

242
00:12:55,480 --> 00:12:58,100
I naturally put all valuables in the closet for the night.

243
00:12:58,260 --> 00:12:59,940
Jesus, you're really a total nutcase.

244
00:13:00,810 --> 00:13:02,190
How dare you talk to me like that?

245
00:13:02,370 --> 00:13:05,650
Your brother is chained up at a construction site, but you're freaking out about a pile of junk.

246
00:13:05,730 --> 00:13:07,610
And because of you I'll be late for the test.

247
00:13:07,850 --> 00:13:09,350
You should be really proud of yourself.

248
00:13:09,430 --> 00:13:10,370
Iva, what is it?

249
00:13:10,550 --> 00:13:11,530
Are you wearing pajamas?

250
00:13:11,770 --> 00:13:14,170
I'd rather go to school in pajamas than miss the Civics test.

251
00:13:14,370 --> 00:13:15,470
I'll change during break.

252
00:13:16,150 --> 00:13:17,950
Ivushka, change here.

253
00:13:18,010 --> 00:13:18,530
I'll write you...

254
00:13:20,710 --> 00:13:21,470
We have Kobra.

255
00:13:21,470 --> 00:13:23,850
Want her to come check our pipes?

256
00:13:24,470 --> 00:13:24,910
Kobra?

257
00:13:26,750 --> 00:13:27,250
Run.

258
00:13:35,500 --> 00:13:36,640
How are you doing, Mr. Ozzak?

259
00:13:36,880 --> 00:13:38,140
It's worse than I thought.

260
00:13:38,360 --> 00:13:38,980
You're a hero.

261
00:13:39,750 --> 00:13:40,850
But I won't last much longer.

262
00:13:41,150 --> 00:13:42,000
Don't worry.

263
00:13:42,350 --> 00:13:43,550
I won't leave you hanging.

264
00:13:43,750 --> 00:13:45,420
I was afraid you'd forgotten about me.

265
00:13:45,420 --> 00:13:46,260
About you?

266
00:13:46,340 --> 00:13:47,520
I thought about it all night.

267
00:13:47,580 --> 00:13:48,200
Me too.

268
00:13:48,280 --> 00:13:49,020
And I've got it.

269
00:13:49,480 --> 00:13:49,920
Hurry.

270
00:13:53,550 --> 00:13:56,050
I'll protest with you and I'm not afraid of Kobra.

271
00:13:58,250 --> 00:13:58,950
Got the bottle?

272
00:14:00,450 --> 00:14:00,950
I'm right-handed.

273
00:14:10,250 --> 00:14:12,450
Hello, have I reached Brno?

274
00:14:13,850 --> 00:14:18,250
What do you mean you can't know, that it depends on where I'm calling?

275
00:14:18,650 --> 00:14:20,550
I'm calling Brno.

276
00:14:21,550 --> 00:14:25,450
I don't understand, I'm calling the wrong Brno?

277
00:14:26,750 --> 00:14:33,550
Oh, Brno with an "i," right, I apologize, but that must happen to you a lot, doesn't it?

278
00:14:34,630 --> 00:14:35,090
It doesn't.

279
00:14:36,290 --> 00:14:36,750
Fine.

280
00:14:41,350 --> 00:14:43,250
We could've been demolishing that kindergarten by now.

281
00:14:43,390 --> 00:14:44,510
You'll pay for this!

282
00:14:44,510 --> 00:14:46,850
I must have left them in the other bulldozer.

283
00:14:47,050 --> 00:14:49,290
Leaves the bolt cutters in the other bulldozer?

284
00:14:49,290 --> 00:14:49,770
Idiot.

285
00:14:52,330 --> 00:14:52,890
You see that?

286
00:14:53,310 --> 00:14:53,930
You see that?

287
00:14:53,930 --> 00:14:55,650
Now there's two of them.

288
00:14:58,020 --> 00:14:58,580
Really?

289
00:14:59,250 --> 00:15:01,840
Go to a hardware store and buy bolt cutters.

290
00:15:01,840 --> 00:15:03,060
And make it snappy!

291
00:15:03,060 --> 00:15:05,050
Or they'll start multiplying on us.

292
00:15:06,050 --> 00:15:06,500
So...

293
00:15:07,150 --> 00:15:08,700
Where'd you even get those handcuffs?

294
00:15:08,700 --> 00:15:09,380
Don't tell.

295
00:15:09,750 --> 00:15:10,660
They're Mom's.

296
00:15:10,750 --> 00:15:13,550
From when she was a mounted police officer.

297
00:15:13,950 --> 00:15:14,670
Seriously?

298
00:15:14,670 --> 00:15:15,130
Yeah.

299
00:15:15,750 --> 00:15:17,450
She's also got a whip and a harness at home.

300
00:15:18,150 --> 00:15:19,150
But I didn't take those.

301
00:15:21,650 --> 00:15:22,170
Hey!

302
00:15:23,250 --> 00:15:24,550
You want to protest too?

303
00:15:26,750 --> 00:15:28,110
Then turn around and get out of here!

304
00:15:28,110 --> 00:15:28,630
Yeah!

305
00:15:32,710 --> 00:15:33,490
Hello, Todor.

306
00:15:33,590 --> 00:15:34,290
Hello, big guy.

307
00:15:34,950 --> 00:15:35,950
Boss, it's far.

308
00:15:37,250 --> 00:15:38,330
Can I borrow the bulldozer?

309
00:15:42,250 --> 00:15:44,350
Well, that's interesting, pork fest.

310
00:15:44,720 --> 00:15:45,240
No.

311
00:15:45,950 --> 00:15:47,850
We don't accept payment in kind.

312
00:15:48,150 --> 00:15:49,150
Goodbye.

313
00:15:51,700 --> 00:15:54,060
Tomas, I've been waiting for you like for salvation.

314
00:15:54,460 --> 00:15:56,360
I called you but your line was always busy.

315
00:15:56,580 --> 00:15:57,100
I've been managing.

316
00:15:57,300 --> 00:15:58,220
What happened?

317
00:15:59,150 --> 00:16:00,350
We're a nation of thieves.

318
00:16:01,050 --> 00:16:02,310
With a useless police force.

319
00:16:02,550 --> 00:16:03,750
For God's sake, what happened?

320
00:16:04,250 --> 00:16:05,050
I was robbed.

321
00:16:05,250 --> 00:16:07,190
Jesus Christ, what did they take?

322
00:16:07,350 --> 00:16:08,070
A bicycle.

323
00:16:08,450 --> 00:16:11,350
And the police has been letting the culprit escape for 8 hours.

324
00:16:11,550 --> 00:16:13,170
Is this about that bicycle of yours?

325
00:16:13,170 --> 00:16:13,510
Yes.

326
00:16:13,850 --> 00:16:15,950
Then don't worry, he couldn't have gotten far.

327
00:16:16,110 --> 00:16:16,630
You think?

328
00:16:17,150 --> 00:16:18,650
I also rode it to the post office.

329
00:16:20,350 --> 00:16:22,800
But I have something for you that might cheer you up.

330
00:16:22,800 --> 00:16:23,560
Your tour.

331
00:16:24,490 --> 00:16:25,890
Do I have a new concert?

332
00:16:25,890 --> 00:16:28,650
Yes, if you don't have a problem with heights.

333
00:16:29,100 --> 00:16:30,880
I'm no Caruso, but...

334
00:16:30,880 --> 00:16:33,220
It's a hunting festival in Zabonosy.

335
00:16:33,280 --> 00:16:34,760
They want you to sing from a deer stand.

336
00:16:37,150 --> 00:16:38,750
Nothing else available?

337
00:16:38,750 --> 00:16:41,860
A kickoff at the stadium in Blsany, but I turned that down.

338
00:16:41,860 --> 00:16:42,740
Why?

339
00:16:42,740 --> 00:16:45,600
I used to play football, even Bohdalka envied my skills.

340
00:16:45,750 --> 00:16:47,650
It's a kickoff for a new sewer.

341
00:16:50,950 --> 00:16:51,990
I'll take the deer stand then.

342
00:16:51,990 --> 00:16:52,550
Excellent.

343
00:16:53,150 --> 00:16:56,150
When Ozzak comes, I'll pop to the post office and send the posters.

344
00:16:56,750 --> 00:16:57,850
Well, that can wait.

345
00:16:58,080 --> 00:16:58,600
Why?

346
00:16:58,680 --> 00:17:00,060
Without the bike I'll be back in five minutes.

347
00:17:00,320 --> 00:17:02,680
Yeah, but Ozzak won't be coming today.

348
00:17:02,720 --> 00:17:04,160
It's kind of an exceptional situation.

349
00:17:06,050 --> 00:17:09,150
You call your brother not coming in an exceptional situation?

350
00:17:09,250 --> 00:17:12,790
He's protesting at the Badger, chained himself to the bar and swallowed the key.

351
00:17:12,790 --> 00:17:14,150
And what's exceptional about that?

352
00:17:14,850 --> 00:17:16,430
Don't worry, she's not that tough.

353
00:17:16,550 --> 00:17:19,010
He's on strike, but don't worry, he'll get over it soon.

354
00:17:19,010 --> 00:17:20,130
I seriously doubt that.

355
00:17:20,830 --> 00:17:24,250
Ozzak's work ethic has always exhibited all the attributes of a strike.

356
00:17:24,350 --> 00:17:25,310
It's just never been declared.

357
00:17:25,790 --> 00:17:27,150
If this keeps up...

358
00:17:28,250 --> 00:17:29,250
I'll form a union.

359
00:17:37,450 --> 00:17:40,550
Yeah, first one and now already two.

360
00:17:41,950 --> 00:17:43,300
This ain't no Palace of Culture.

361
00:17:43,750 --> 00:17:45,450
We're supposed to be tearing down the pub.

362
00:17:46,150 --> 00:17:48,270
Well, I'm waiting now.

363
00:17:49,550 --> 00:17:51,250
So what the hell am I supposed to do?

364
00:17:52,020 --> 00:17:53,460
No, I already asked about that.

365
00:17:53,540 --> 00:17:54,580
No demands whatsoever.

366
00:17:55,450 --> 00:17:56,730
Yeah, well, they want a bottle.

367
00:17:56,730 --> 00:17:57,330
An empty one.

368
00:17:57,330 --> 00:17:58,730
Well, what for I don't know.

369
00:17:58,730 --> 00:18:00,950
Shove that bottle up your ass, you murderer!

370
00:18:01,330 --> 00:18:01,930
Heroes!

371
00:18:03,130 --> 00:18:04,690
So they don't want the bottle anymore.

372
00:18:05,650 --> 00:18:07,150
And they're calling me a pub murderer.

373
00:18:07,550 --> 00:18:10,230
Look, Mr. Hajek, I don't need this.

374
00:18:10,450 --> 00:18:14,250
If there are kids chained up in that kindergarten, I'm done with this.

375
00:18:14,750 --> 00:18:21,790
I must be dreaming.

376
00:18:21,950 --> 00:18:23,090
So what's going on here?

377
00:18:31,250 --> 00:18:35,050
So Shaun Bucek is actually demonstrating.

378
00:18:36,650 --> 00:18:38,050
Who's that next to him?

379
00:18:38,850 --> 00:18:40,550
Ma'am, you have no business here.

380
00:18:45,580 --> 00:18:47,580
You recognized me, you owl of a professor?

381
00:18:47,800 --> 00:18:52,000
Well, that mug of yours will haunt me for the rest of my life.

382
00:18:54,150 --> 00:19:00,710
Look, madam, I don't know who you are, but take your little debate club and go somewhere, like a park.

383
00:19:00,950 --> 00:19:02,450
This is a construction site!

384
00:19:02,750 --> 00:19:04,850
Do you have a building permit?

385
00:19:05,250 --> 00:19:06,110
Of course.

386
00:19:06,250 --> 00:19:07,250
Outside in the bulldozer.

387
00:19:07,650 --> 00:19:09,610
There's no bulldozer outside.

388
00:19:09,850 --> 00:19:12,550
Well, because the big guy drove it to get scissors.

389
00:19:13,540 --> 00:19:14,080
Naturally.

390
00:19:15,350 --> 00:19:23,150
This is as absurd as when Buckova told me that Bucek was demonstrating against world globalization instead of attending my class.

391
00:19:26,950 --> 00:19:31,350
It seems, however, that today is indeed inclined toward absurdity.

392
00:19:31,350 --> 00:19:34,950
What are you doing here, Pacovsky?

393
00:19:35,450 --> 00:19:37,150
I want my pub back.

394
00:19:37,450 --> 00:19:39,050
I apologize, Buckova.

395
00:19:39,650 --> 00:19:43,050
So you're here on behalf of a multinational corporation.

396
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:46,600
Help him, Buckova.

397
00:19:46,660 --> 00:19:48,800
Multinational corporations are the engine of globalization.

398
00:19:48,800 --> 00:19:55,500
To achieve their goals, they use international capital and exploit cheap labor, primarily from third world countries.

399
00:19:55,750 --> 00:19:56,380
Jesus.

400
00:19:56,380 --> 00:19:57,860
Those few Bulgarians...

401
00:19:57,860 --> 00:19:59,140
So, yes.

402
00:20:00,050 --> 00:20:02,750
And what has been your course of action so far?

403
00:20:03,250 --> 00:20:04,650
I sent the big guy for scissors.

404
00:20:05,810 --> 00:20:07,730
I obviously didn't teach you.

405
00:20:07,730 --> 00:20:14,050
Otherwise you'd know that a civil protest requires...

406
00:20:16,550 --> 00:20:17,660
So, the rest.

407
00:20:17,660 --> 00:20:17,980
Yeah.

408
00:20:18,220 --> 00:20:19,000
Bottles.

409
00:20:19,750 --> 00:20:21,050
Empty bottles.

410
00:20:21,150 --> 00:20:22,950
Without citizens.

411
00:20:23,150 --> 00:20:24,020
Buckova.

412
00:20:24,350 --> 00:20:25,750
Without police assistance.

413
00:20:25,880 --> 00:20:26,720
Excellent.

414
00:20:28,050 --> 00:20:30,150
So, what are you waiting for?

415
00:20:39,050 --> 00:20:41,740
You're not protesting by any chance...

416
00:20:42,050 --> 00:20:44,750
...just to skip the test?

417
00:20:44,780 --> 00:20:45,380
No.

418
00:20:45,380 --> 00:20:49,350
You know, you're lucky.

419
00:20:50,050 --> 00:20:53,650
I happen to have it right here for you.

420
00:20:53,950 --> 00:20:58,450
Professor, professor, couldn't we maybe take the test again?

421
00:20:58,750 --> 00:21:01,140
Don't you have any more classes?

422
00:21:01,350 --> 00:21:04,450
We have biology, practical study of urban birds.

423
00:21:05,750 --> 00:21:08,540
I'll arrange it with colleague Dvorsky.

424
00:21:08,540 --> 00:21:11,460
Feeding pigeons isn't in the curriculum anyway.

425
00:21:11,780 --> 00:21:13,680
But I already took the test.

426
00:21:14,750 --> 00:21:16,350
With a D.

427
00:21:17,650 --> 00:21:19,550
So you'll be happy to improve it.

428
00:21:20,050 --> 00:21:27,950
Well, Bucek, why aren't you writing?

429
00:21:29,550 --> 00:21:31,850
Pacovsky will gladly help you.

430
00:21:32,450 --> 00:21:35,880
Professor, we really need to use the bathroom.

431
00:21:36,450 --> 00:21:47,650
I've had thirty students, but only one ever surpassed you in the brazenness of excuses.

432
00:21:48,450 --> 00:21:49,030
Buckova.

433
00:21:49,250 --> 00:21:51,750
Student Dutohlav, professor.

434
00:21:56,050 --> 00:22:02,450
No, Marcelka, I know a Guinness record entry would help us, but I won't hang by my feet from a crane.

435
00:22:03,650 --> 00:22:05,250
Not even over a pond.

436
00:22:06,450 --> 00:22:07,650
Wait, they're here.

437
00:22:09,850 --> 00:22:10,720
Finally.

438
00:22:10,720 --> 00:22:11,920
You're the one with the bicycle.

439
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:12,820
Yes, come in.

440
00:22:14,150 --> 00:22:17,150
You took your time, I hope it's not too late.

441
00:22:19,090 --> 00:22:19,890
What's this?

442
00:22:20,350 --> 00:22:21,250
A scent sample.

443
00:22:21,750 --> 00:22:22,660
A scent sample?

444
00:22:22,660 --> 00:22:23,180
For the dog.

445
00:22:24,450 --> 00:22:25,350
What dog?

446
00:22:26,450 --> 00:22:27,250
A police dog.

447
00:22:27,910 --> 00:22:28,430
Ah.

448
00:22:29,050 --> 00:22:30,410
So, your ID please.

449
00:22:30,630 --> 00:22:32,050
Pull out form seventeen, Becka.

450
00:22:32,450 --> 00:22:34,850
Twelve, surely? Seventeen is scrap metal theft.

451
00:22:35,610 --> 00:22:36,130
Ah.

452
00:22:38,460 --> 00:22:40,300
So where did you keep the bicycle?

453
00:22:40,620 --> 00:22:41,440
In the basement.

454
00:22:45,150 --> 00:22:48,050
There was no chain, so it was unsecured.

455
00:22:48,970 --> 00:22:50,570
Hummingbird 9, do you read me?

456
00:22:50,810 --> 00:22:51,870
Hummingbird 9, copy.

457
00:22:52,850 --> 00:22:53,850
Are you at Horakova's yet?

458
00:22:54,150 --> 00:22:55,450
Yeah, we're already investigating.

459
00:22:56,950 --> 00:22:59,720
Forget that, we've got a two-oh-five at the Badger restaurant, Kestoci street.

460
00:22:59,720 --> 00:23:04,450
Good grief, we don't have the equipment for a two-oh-five, have them send the fire department.

461
00:23:04,650 --> 00:23:07,930
Firefighters are in demand these days, they all have day jobs, don't want to get dirty.

462
00:23:09,330 --> 00:23:12,230
Excuse me, can I ask what a two-oh-five means?

463
00:23:12,350 --> 00:23:17,250
Those are codes for dangerous situations, for example two-eleven is acid in a bathtub, two-nineteen is mayor in danger.

464
00:23:17,330 --> 00:23:19,330
Man, I'm asking what two-oh-five means?

465
00:23:19,610 --> 00:23:20,370
Protest by vagrants.

466
00:23:22,650 --> 00:23:23,090
Poor thing!

467
00:23:25,760 --> 00:23:26,300
See that?

468
00:23:27,750 --> 00:23:30,950
Leaves his apartment unlocked and then wonders someone stole his bike.

469
00:23:39,650 --> 00:23:40,350
Mr. Hajek, it's Burda.

470
00:23:41,450 --> 00:23:42,530
Yeah, the pub.

471
00:23:44,150 --> 00:23:45,250
Shhh, I already handled it.

472
00:23:45,450 --> 00:23:46,950
I called the police.

473
00:23:47,930 --> 00:23:49,330
Don't worry, they'll be right there.

474
00:23:49,330 --> 00:23:54,530
I told them the big guy is going to take down half the block along with those lunatics.

475
00:23:54,950 --> 00:23:56,050
What a great idea.

476
00:23:56,650 --> 00:23:58,550
I made it up.

477
00:24:00,790 --> 00:24:01,350
Ozzak!

478
00:24:03,430 --> 00:24:03,990
Iva!

479
00:24:04,370 --> 00:24:04,750
Quiet!

480
00:24:05,950 --> 00:24:07,550
She's in the back grading tests.

481
00:24:07,640 --> 00:24:08,400
Who, what?

482
00:24:08,950 --> 00:24:09,450
Keep it down.

483
00:24:09,650 --> 00:24:11,950
Yeah, I hear.

484
00:24:14,390 --> 00:24:15,530
Where on earth did she come from?

485
00:24:17,650 --> 00:24:18,750
And she gave me a test.

486
00:24:19,840 --> 00:24:21,260
Bro, I can't take it here anymore.

487
00:24:22,270 --> 00:24:23,110
Got the Smurf?

488
00:24:24,050 --> 00:24:28,750
So what's going on here?

489
00:24:34,250 --> 00:24:35,550
You know her too?

490
00:24:37,320 --> 00:24:38,100
She checked my ears.

491
00:24:38,220 --> 00:24:39,650
What the hell is she doing here?

492
00:24:40,240 --> 00:24:41,420
Grading tests.

493
00:24:41,950 --> 00:24:43,050
Is this place yours?

494
00:24:43,250 --> 00:24:47,200
Well, it was, until this guy chained himself to the bar and refused to budge.

495
00:24:47,200 --> 00:24:48,220
I really gotta go now.

496
00:24:48,360 --> 00:24:49,880
Hey, this guy wants out.

497
00:24:49,900 --> 00:24:51,240
Why haven't you cut him loose ages ago?

498
00:24:51,420 --> 00:24:52,540
We don't have bolt cutters.

499
00:24:52,680 --> 00:24:53,080
Right?!

500
00:24:54,230 --> 00:24:54,770
Sorry.

501
00:24:55,650 --> 00:24:56,750
Someone stole my bulldozer.

502
00:24:58,180 --> 00:24:58,720
From you?

503
00:24:59,350 --> 00:25:00,750
Right now?

504
00:25:01,650 --> 00:25:11,590
How could someone steal your bulldozer?

505
00:25:11,590 --> 00:25:12,530
I don't know.

506
00:25:12,530 --> 00:25:15,910
I parked in front of Harold's and when I came back, it was gone.

507
00:25:15,910 --> 00:25:17,250
Were you in a handicapped spot?

508
00:25:18,520 --> 00:25:19,080
Damn.

509
00:25:20,450 --> 00:25:22,030
You idiots!

510
00:25:24,350 --> 00:25:26,170
Guys, are you nuts?

511
00:25:26,170 --> 00:25:27,790
Can't you just cut me loose?

512
00:25:28,050 --> 00:25:29,270
Just go around him and climb out.

513
00:25:30,150 --> 00:25:32,250
No, that chain is mine.

514
00:25:32,450 --> 00:25:35,450
One more word and I'll haul you in for a patrol.

515
00:25:47,050 --> 00:25:48,950
They won't get away from me, you know that.

516
00:25:49,890 --> 00:25:50,870
Hold on to this.

517
00:25:56,820 --> 00:25:59,040
Well, it's gotten a bit...

518
00:25:59,160 --> 00:25:59,600
Thin.

519
00:26:00,940 --> 00:26:02,280
Where are the others?

520
00:26:02,980 --> 00:26:03,580
They left.

521
00:26:03,960 --> 00:26:04,560
Why?

522
00:26:05,350 --> 00:26:07,720
I think they were afraid of you, professor.

523
00:26:08,250 --> 00:26:09,850
And you're not afraid of me?

524
00:26:10,380 --> 00:26:11,300
We are, actually.

525
00:26:11,300 --> 00:26:14,050
But you stayed.

526
00:26:15,150 --> 00:26:27,150
If I also found Bucek here with you, I'd start thinking that finally a generation has come that has courage, doesn't run away, and doesn't hide behind stupid excuses.

527
00:26:29,350 --> 00:26:31,450
Sorry, I got locked in the bathroom.

528
00:26:31,750 --> 00:26:36,350
Well, see, maybe you've held up after all.

529
00:26:36,950 --> 00:26:39,050
Dude, I don't have the guts.

530
00:26:39,580 --> 00:26:40,240
You do.

531
00:26:42,280 --> 00:26:43,320
Yeah, and for what?

532
00:26:45,550 --> 00:26:49,350
Maybe for writing that Vaclav Havel wrote "The Piss of the Powerless."

533
00:27:01,450 --> 00:27:02,350
So it's raining now?

534
00:27:03,050 --> 00:27:04,090
Oh, that's great.

535
00:27:04,450 --> 00:27:05,850
So shall we set something up?

536
00:27:06,750 --> 00:27:08,950
Ah, raining too much.

537
00:27:09,750 --> 00:27:11,150
I'll call again then.

538
00:27:13,050 --> 00:27:14,450
The dry region is out too.

539
00:27:16,850 --> 00:27:18,750
So that just leaves Blsany.

540
00:27:25,620 --> 00:27:26,100
Bro!

541
00:27:26,850 --> 00:27:27,820
Where did you find it?

542
00:27:27,950 --> 00:27:28,920
Right around the corner.

543
00:27:29,150 --> 00:27:30,550
Just past the scrap yard.

544
00:27:31,050 --> 00:27:33,940
What kind of barbarian would want to scrap this thing?

545
00:27:34,050 --> 00:27:34,640
I know.

546
00:27:34,750 --> 00:27:37,740
Some guy was hunched over it, reeked of gasoline and asked me for matches.

547
00:27:37,740 --> 00:27:39,500
And I'll go buy a new chain right away.

548
00:27:39,700 --> 00:27:40,040
Yeah.

549
00:27:41,910 --> 00:27:42,390
Sorry.

550
00:27:43,150 --> 00:27:43,680
One more thing.

551
00:27:43,680 --> 00:27:44,000
Yeah.

552
00:27:46,650 --> 00:27:47,950
You know what, bro?

553
00:27:48,450 --> 00:27:49,450
You can keep it.

554
00:27:50,150 --> 00:27:50,850
Really?

555
00:27:51,620 --> 00:27:52,100
Awesome!
